  editor    = {John W. Schwieter},
  pages     = {234--254},
  address   = {Cambridge, England},
  abstract  = {In this chapter, Ellis and associates, first, outline usage-based factors which determine first and second language learning alike and, second, report three studies on the use and acquisition of English verb-argument constructions (VACs) ['he ___ across the...', 'it ___ of the...']. First, they highlight the role of three factors in language learning which provide evidence for the usage-based nature of language learning. Language processing and acquisition is sensitive to input frequencies of constructions and associated verbs, the contingency of form-function mappings, and the prototypicality of meanings. Ellis and associates conducted a corpus study to investigate the usage of English VACs. Statistical analysis of data from the British National Corpus (BNC) revealed that (1) the most frequent verb takes the lion's share of the uses of each VAC (Zipfian distribution), (2) the most frequent verb in each VAC is prototypical of the respective construction's meaning, (3) particular verbs select particular constructions and vice versa, and (4) VACs are coherent in their semantics, that is, they are used with a set of verbs which form semantic networks. In the following sections, Ellis and associates report empirical studies which relate the results of the corpus study to empirical data elicited in free associations tasks to show that first and second language learning alike are affected by verb frequency in the VACs, VAC-verb contingency and semantic prototypicality of the verbs in terms of their centrality in the VAC semantic network. Moreover, comparing German, Czech and Spanish learners of English to each other and to native users of English, first language transfer becomes apparent: learners whose first language is satellite framed (German, Czech) and hence similar to English produced VAC verbs in the experiments similar to native users of English and correlated with usage data from the corpus study, whereas learners whose first language is verb framed (Spanish) deviated in their productions from the other learners and natives productions and native usage. Since second language learners have already acquired a language, their second language intake is affected by transfer, first-language-tuned expectations and selective attention rendering biased intake from naturalistic usage. ``Second language constructions thus demonstrate effects of L2 and L1 usage.'' (254) [Note that the BNC frequencies were used in the L1 as well as in the L2 studies.]},
